column3: CONSENT    Dear Healthcare worker or trainee,    Quality of care and patient safety is increasingly becoming a concern worldwide with little attempt in teaching and assessing patient safety at in-service, diploma, under-graduate and even at residency levels in medical education in the African context.    You are being invited to share your views about the level of training available or needed to support health care workers in the science, methods, and practical application of the principles of quality improvement and patient safety in your institution.    Please share openly and honestly. Your responses will be anonymous and your participation is strictly voluntary.  You have the right to refuse to participate or answer any questions that you feel uncomfortable with. If you change your mind about participating during the course of this study, you have the right to withdraw at any time.    There are no questions about your own individual health status. This is about training: training you are teaching or training have experienced or needs you see for training in quality and patient safety.     Risks  -The information you will provide during the study will be kept in confidence.   -There is minimal to no risk to students, staff or healthcare workers in participating in these interviews.   -No individual clinical information is requested.   -All information is about training and training needs and is part of public knowledge in the institution.   -All pre-service curriculum specifics are also known to the relevant health care worker licensing body.   -All information shall be kept confidential and inform the gap and the implementation of an integrated curriculum for knowledge and skills development.    Benefits  -By participating in this study and answering the questions you will help in providing information that will improve the quality of care and the training of healthcare workers in the respective departments.   -This will also ultimately contribute to the improvement of healthcare training and services, benefiting both the individual participants and the broader community.    The Principal investigator is Lydia Okutoyi from Health care Quality KNH. Principal investigator's contacts are 0721814381. The PI is supported by Dr Carolyne Mukuha  0721964285     If you have any concerns about how this study is being conducted, you can get in touch with the secretary of Kenyatta National Hospital-University of Nairobi Research and ethics Committee through the following contacts: KNH/UoN - ERC P.O. Box 20723-00203 or  Email: uonknh_erc@uonbi.ac.ke or Tel. 726300-9 Monday to Friday from 9.00am to 5.00 pm.    Your participation in the online REDCAP survey is evidence of your consent.     Declaration of the respondent    I have understood the purpose of this study and, therefore, consent voluntarily to participate as a respondent.
